WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:05.280
&gt;&gt; From the library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:07.490 --> 00:00:09.180
&gt;&gt;Aimee Picard Soller:
Our author today,

00:00:09.180 --> 00:00:12.410
Chris Bohjalian describes
himself in a social media bio

00:00:12.410 --> 00:00:16.240
as author, bicyclist, and gym rat.

00:00:16.240 --> 00:00:17.960
He is those things I'm sure,

00:00:17.960 --> 00:00:21.550
as well as New York Times
best-selling author of 19 books.

00:00:21.550 --> 00:00:25.820
His novel, Midwives, was a number
one New York Times best seller,

00:00:25.820 --> 00:00:30.400
a selection of Oprah's book club,
a publishers weekly best book,

00:00:30.400 --> 00:00:34.440
and a New England Booksellers
Association discovery pick.

00:00:34.440 --> 00:00:37.840
His work has been translated
into over 30 languages

00:00:37.840 --> 00:00:39.250
and three motion pictures.

00:00:39.250 --> 00:00:41.360
And, a fourth is in the works

00:00:41.360 --> 00:00:45.110
with the Sandcastle Girls being
adapted from a feature film.

00:00:45.110 --> 00:00:48.860
He's written for many
publications including the Times,

00:00:48.860 --> 00:00:52.690
the Washington Post,
Cosmopolitan, and Readers Digest.

00:00:52.690 --> 00:00:53.990
He is currently a fellow

00:00:53.990 --> 00:00:55.670
of the Vermont academy
of arts and sciences.

00:00:55.670 --> 00:00:57.640
And his latest novel,

00:00:57.640 --> 00:01:00.630
"The Sleepwalkers" was
released in January.

00:01:00.630 --> 00:01:03.670
And, readers can anxiously
anticipate his next novel,

00:01:03.670 --> 00:01:05.610
The Flight Attendant, in March.

00:01:05.610 --> 00:01:10.050
Chris's awards include the
Armenian National Committee

00:01:10.050 --> 00:01:13.340
of American Freedom Award for
his work in educating Americans

00:01:13.340 --> 00:01:15.750
about the Armenian genocide.

00:01:15.750 --> 00:01:19.310
The Armenian National Committee
of America Arts and Letters Award

00:01:19.310 --> 00:01:21.280
for the Sandcastle Girls.

00:01:21.280 --> 00:01:24.880
The New England Society Book
Award for the Night Strangers.

00:01:24.880 --> 00:01:26.860
The New England Book Award.

00:01:26.860 --> 00:01:30.120
Russia's Concord Award
for the Sandcastle Girls.

00:01:30.120 --> 00:01:32.490
A Boston public library
literary light.

00:01:32.490 --> 00:01:37.670
A finalist for the Lamda Literary
Awards for Trans Sister Radio.

00:01:37.670 --> 00:01:40.670
A best lifestyle column
for Idyll Banter,

00:01:40.670 --> 00:01:43.030
and the Vermont Press Association.

00:01:43.030 --> 00:01:47.800
Fans of his work marvel at his
ability to develop a character

00:01:47.800 --> 00:01:50.160
with such depth and
article language.

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:52.390
He says that he allows
the characters to develop

00:01:52.390 --> 00:01:54.710
and lead him through the stories.

00:01:54.710 --> 00:01:57.490
His books are always
edited using a fountain pen

00:01:57.490 --> 00:02:02.390
as he says they are messy and
they force you to think slowly.

00:02:02.390 --> 00:02:04.470
Chris has said that he
found his voice in Vermont

00:02:04.470 --> 00:02:06.880
where he lives with
his wife Victoria.

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:09.820
That is there he was able to
develop the novels and characters

00:02:09.820 --> 00:02:12.300
that readers have come
to know and love.

00:02:12.300 --> 00:02:14.800
We are very glad that he's
brought his voice here to DC

00:02:14.800 --> 00:02:17.420 position:56%
in the national book festival today.

00:02:17.420 --> 00:02:19.850
Please note that after
Chris's remarks he will be

00:02:19.850 --> 00:02:23.970
in the book signing section
from 1 to 2 p.m. Please join me

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:35.560
in welcoming Chris to
the festival stage.

